Exploratory: Correlation Between Facebook Social Conectedness Index and UN’s Migrant Stock

Data sources

  • Iso codes, region, and income level: 📦 {wbstats} and 📦{countrycodes} R packages. This analysis excludes observations that are not present in the World Bank’s list of countries.

  • Facebook’s Social Connectedness Index : It measures the relative probability of a Facebook friendship link between a given Facebook user in location i and a user in location j. Put differently, if this measure is twice as large, a Facebook user in i is about twice as likely to be connected with a given Facebook user in j. SCI excludes the following areas: Afghanistan, Western Sahara, China, Cuba, Iraq, Israel, Iran, North Korea, Russia, Syria, Somalia, South Sudan, Sudan, Venezuela, Yemen, Crimea, Jammu and Kashmir, Donetsk, Luhansk, Sevastopol, West Bank, and Gaza.

  • UN Migrant Stock By Origin And Destination : The total migrant stock at mid-year by origin and country of destination

  • World Bank’s Total Population : Total population by country, accessed via 📦 {wbstats} in R.

Clean data

Because the SCI data contains only information for 2019, the clean version of the “joint/merged” dataset only includes data for this year and for countries that are included in all the data sources (UN Stocks, Facebook SCI, World Bank’s Total Population). The iso codes were used to define A unique bilateral identifier for each combination of countries. A second identifier was created to identify the direction of the relationship between countries.

The variables stocks_bilateral, flow_origin and flow_destination were calculated using UN’s Migration Stock.
